Acute megakaryoblastic leukemia in children and adolescents: a retrospective 
analysis of 24 cases.

Ribeiro RC(1), Oliveira MS, Fairclough D, Hurwitz C, Mirro J, Behm FG, Head D, 
Silva ML, Raimondi SC, Crist WM, et al.

Author information:
(1)Department of Hematology-Oncology, St. Jude Children's Research Hospital, 
Memphis, Tennessee 38105.

In order to characterize the clinical, cytogenetic, and outcome features of 
childhood acute megakaryoblastic leukemia (AMKL), we reviewed 24 cases; 14 were 
identified among 150 consecutive newly diagnosed acute myelogenous leukemia 
(AML) patients at St. Jude Children's Research Hospital, and 10 were cases 
referred to the National Institute of Cancer in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. There 
were 5 Down syndrome patients and one patient with chronic myeloid leukemia 
(Ph+) in blastic crisis. Twelve patients had significant hepatosplenomegaly. 
Leukemic cell morphology and cytochemistry were consistent with the M7 
classification in 17 cases, and all cases tested expressed megakaryocytic 
surface antigens. AMKL patients were significantly younger than other AML 
patients (P = 0.0001) and had poorer responses to therapy (P = 0.03, univariate 
analysis only). Ten of 24 failed induction, and only 5 are disease-free at 6 
months to 4.5+ years. We conclude that AMKL usually affects young children, 
frequently producing marked organomegaly. It comprises approximately 10% of 
pediatric AML cases, and responds poorly to intensive AML therapies.

